column168: Arrived at customers facility at roughly 9:30am to offload hypochlorite solution into consignee's tank. This tank was a non dot HDPE storage tank. This tank is not used for transportation purposes according to the consignee. It is strictly a storage tank that hypochlorite is stored in before being used in accordance with MSDS recommended usage for pool water treatment. The driver connected delivery hose and started the offloading process. After off loading roughly 200 gallons into the consignee storage tank, spillage became visible. The driver immediately closed off all valves on the CTMV. After climbing around the consignee's storage tank he found the tank adapter that is used for offloading from the storage tank into the consignees smaller containers was leaking profusely. Within minutes the contents of the tank leaked onto the consignee's private property. The driver secured the scene and notified the customer and Poolsure management team of the spill. Shortly after the customer bermed the area and developed a plan for clean. After Poolsure management arrived on scene and gathered data the driver was released from the scene by Poolsure management team. The consignee agreed to privately handle the remediation in accordance with MSDS recommendations.
column169: Poolsure will no longer supply this customer with hypochlorite solution unless a containment is used even though the containment for this storage amount is not required by law. As a responsible chemical distributor we choose to no longer deliver to consignees with these type of tanks with tank adapters unless a failure is containable.

column62: Valve Open; Missing Component or Device
column168: At approximately 0825 hrs on 7/7/2014 I,John Vergis, was called by our Division Superintendent, Jim Hill, about a leaking Natural Gasoline car in our "Hartland Yard" in Collins, Ohio.  I was told that the car was leaking from the manyway as it was sitting still. I called Chemtrec at 0845 to make the initial spill notification.  MarkWest in Denver, CO contacted me at 0900 hrs. to discuss.  Rick Kline from the MarkWest plant that loaded the car called me at 0915 to see what was going on.  I told him of the situation and he said he was going to contact his Emergency Response Contractor to come look at the situation.  I arrived on scene at 1010 hrs.  When I approached the car I noticed a 4 foot wide stream of product running down the car onto the ground.  The liquid was coming from the "Bread Box".  I climbed the car to investigate and find that the Sample line valve inside the Bread Box Dome was in the fully open position and that the valve plug was not installed.  I shut the valve, reinstalled the plug and released the car back into service at approximately 1035 hours.  According to the MarkWest facility, when the car was loaded, it had 13 inches of outage. I checked the car after it was secured, and the guage read 17 inches of outage.  The Emergency Response Contractor arrived at the same time as I did and started to dig a ditch on either side of the rail and install absorbent boom in the ditch to catch any product that may migrate out after a rain event.  Ohio EPA was also notified and a report number was issued.  The ditches and absorbent boom that was installed will be monitored for a minimum of three weeks or until it is determined that no more product, if any, will seep from the road bed.
column169: A more thorough securment procedure needs to be followed before a car is released for shipment.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: After arrival of an inbound BNSF train in the railyard, entrained tank car TILX 194068 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected TILX 194068. The responder reported that the BOV's operating handle's retaining pin had broken with its remnants hanging from the pin retention chain. The unpinned BOV operating handle moved downward into a slightly open position. This opened the BOV and the accumulating commodity seeped out at the threaded connection of the bottom outlet valve's closure cap (BOC). The responder closed the BOV by moving the BOV's operating handle to the closed position and installed a bolt with nut fastener to hold the BOV operating handle upward in the closed position. Afterwards, the commodity drips from the BOC's threaded connection ceased. The BOC securement was inspected and the BOC was tool tightened by 1/4 turn. All spillage evaporated.
column169: No additional comments.

Forklift operator punctured tote with forks while attempting to unload. Material spilled on concrete dock. Fumes from acid reaction with concrete caused minor respiratory irritation to 2 employees. Area was immediately evacuated and a 3rd party hazardous materials response team (ERS Environemnetal)was dicpatched to the scene. Fire Dept. arrived on scene and kept impacted area clear until response team arrived about 1 hr. later. Response team transferred the product from the leaking IBC into a new IBC and completely remediated the impacted area. There was no release onto ground or waterways. All residue and waste was properly packaged and removed by the response team for proper disposal.   Both employees were observed and released from a local hospital. Once remediation was complete the Fire Dept. allowed the area to reopen and normal activity resumed.  Incident reported to NRC report# 1088370 and Michigan DEP # 1-27351068.

According to the initial police report, third party witness statement, and investigation of the accident scene reveals the employee failed to stop at the bottom of the ramp as posted. The employee tried to make the left hand turn at an excessive speed. The speed caused enough side force on the totes to enable their weight to overcome the weight and stability of the trailer. The result was the gooseneck trailer lying on its side along with the totes. The totes leaked approximately 150 gallons of HCL onto the ground thru the top vents before the emergency response team arrived to stop the leaks and begin cleanup. The emergency response team transferred the HCL inside the leaking totes into an empty tote, and transport truck provided by Veolia. Soda ash was spread on the ground under the direction of the DEP to neutralize the HCL that leaked from the totes. No additional cleanup or remediation was required.

The roll off container CHIU258070 on booking TX3763434 was loaded to the Horizon Discovery.  Later, the mate discovered that the container had leaked a black tar like substance on to the two container stowed below it and on the deck of the vessel.  The local USCG, National Response Center and the shipper, Clean Harbors, were contacted.  The shipper also spoke with the EQB in San Juan.  Clean Harbors responded to the incident.  The containers were taken off the vessel and the vessel as well as the two containers stowed below the referenced roll off were cleaned of the spill.  The container that leaked was secured and taken back to Clean Harbors for further correction.  The .5 gallon of contamination was from the "splash" caused by the solidifying process of the product on site at Puma Energy Caribe.  The spill was caused by the failure of Clean Harbors Employees to clean the container "splash".  The liner held the actual solid waste was intact.
column169: Care should be taken in the preparation of the cargo for loading into the roll off container.  Good Housekeeping should be exercised in the cleaning of any residue on the equipment before transferring it to a connecting carrier.

column168: The Driver reported being cut off, locking brakes, and feeling something shift in his load. As he was looking for a location to pull over to investigate, he noticed liquid dripping from rear of the truck (~3:40 PM). The truck was immediately stopped and secured in the street (going Northbound on Ashland approaching the corner of Roosevelt). Based on the Drivers statements, and the vehicle inspection shortly thereafter, it appears the tote was secured using a E-Track Ratchet Style Strap on the passenger side rear. A drum dolly was stored near the front of the compartment which appears to have come loose and punctured the IBC bottle in two locations. Both punctures are located on the back side of the tote (opposite of the valve), and were found to matched up with the handles of the drum dolly. One hole located on the bottom corner (~2 inches)and the other being a tear (~10 inches) mid-way up the center (between the cage bars).Based on the size and location of the pictures, the IBC would have completely empties in a few minutes. The Police and Fire Department arrived within minutes to secure the area. SET Environmental was dispatch to address the vehicle decontamination, neutralization and cleanup activities (i.e. street). The truck was towed away around 11:00 PM allowing them to clean the concrete road underneath (Job completed ~12:00 AM). When the truck was returned for inspection, it was noted that the E-Track was pulled away from the truck wall having with a small tear/crack in the metal fastening location. The ratchet strap and clips appear otherwise intact (simply pulled out from the point of attachment).
column169: The incident appears to be two fold. Firstly, the E-Track breaking free from the truck wall causing the strap to brake free. And secondly, a drum dolly that was not properly secured. As the truck is relatively new (~ 2 years old) an inquired will be made to the manufacture regarding the design/materials selected. As for the Driver's accountability, securing all products and equipment remains a daily point of focus.

column168: On 07/05/2014 at 06:27 hours, personnel in the CSXT Buffalo Frontier Yard discovered PROX 44184 a loaded, UN 1267 tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, DPTS Marketing, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-07-05-00003. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo Branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the PRD  Reclosing Valve was broken.  Mr. Paul Ferguson, Rail Logistics Manager, Cell: 612-849-0628 was notified of the situation found and RESCAR will make the repair by replacement of the PRD  Reclosing Valve    This incident DID require a special move.    Cause Code: 418 (2 points)  NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0)  = 40
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On June 17th at 1130 hours FRA Inspector David Snyder discovered UTLX200329, a residue tank car of Methanol releasing vapors from the vacuum relief valve in Charlestons Cooper Yard.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Koch Fertilizer was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2014-07-14-00182.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a deteriorated vacuum relief valve O-ring.  The defective valve was removed and a plug was installed to contain the escape of vapors.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Kochs representative Chris Avila at 316-828-8797.  Koch has been informed that this rail car requires an OTMA or qualified repair prior to being forwarded to destination.  This incident required a special switching move.    5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70 NARRI

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that material had escaped from a vertical stress line due to bulging along the sides from the weekend's heat. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the two compromised container into a suitable 95- gallon salvage drum. Three other drums were seen to be bulging and as a precaustion were also overpacked using SOP handling of bulging drums.  In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into 1H2 55- gallon poly drum. Once complete, the containers were placed onto the trailer and secured for continued transportation to the appropriate designation facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and has been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: Tank car GATX 5915 was reported venting and expelling commodity from its top fitting area in the railyard's bowl track after being humped. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected GATX 5915 and reported finding the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured (most likely caused by a hydraulic pressure surge event). The frangible disc was replaced in kind. GATX 5915 was cordoned-off awaiting contract responders arrival to neutralize and clean the commodity spillage from GATX 5915's shell and a small area of ground impact around GATX 5915. The response contractor utilized a soda ash/water solution to neutralize ground impacted ballast, ties and soils. Impacted ballast and soils were excavated and placed into two disposal drums which were earmarked for appropriate disposal. The excavated site was backfilled with native soils and clean ballast; and graded to duplicate surrounding profiles. Spillage on GATX 5915 was neutralized and pressure-washed. Captured rinsate was discharged into the facility's waste water treatment plant system.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Undeclared hazmat was found during screening. Local FAA hazmat agents were notified. Shipper was UPS. Shipment did not travel on Alaska Airlines. UPS info as follows:    UPS tracking #: 1Z E93 15W 03 9198 9623    Shipper:    TECH SERVICE PRODUCTS INC   101 ROW 3   LAFAYETTE, LA 70508    Consignee:       POUCH 34-0130 BUILDING 30   NORTH SLOPE BOROUGH   PRUDHOE BAY, AK 99734

At 2030 ET hours, Robert Jackson of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding a release of an unknown amount of a UN1593 DICHLOROMETHANE to the rear of a trailer at the Chicago, IL. terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. The RQ for UN1593 is 1000 pounds. ERTS has requested a copy of the MSDS & BOL and will make any appropriate regulatory reporting. It was reported that facility personnel noticed the leak and cleared the area and reported it. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA of 2 hours to site. The shipper is NEXEO solutions.The contractor is on site and reports 1 drum is forked and released product to trailer floor and 1 drum has a crease mark apparently made by a tow motor fork but is not leaking. The contractor is donning proper PPE and will begin clean up operations. It was reported that facility personnel applied absorbents to the floor of the trailer prior to contractor arrival. The contractor reports approximately 3 (three) gallons of product was released. The leaking drum was over packed. The damaged drum was also over packed (both put is 85 gallon steel over packs and labelled accordingly). All wastes have been collected and containerized. 1-55 gallon drum of wastes was generated and taken for profiling and proper disposal by contractor.

At 2205ET hours, Mike Hart of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding a release of approximately 1/2 gallon of a UN1247 METHYL METHACRYLATE MONOMER from a 5 (five) gallon metal pail to the rear of a trailer and the skid it was loaded on. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. The shipper is Res Tek Inc. this incident does require a Chemtrec notification. UN1247 has a RQ of 1000 pounds. It was reported that facility personnel punctured the pail during loading resulting in the release. After reviewing the ERG, it was decided that a contractor response is necessary. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA to site of 90 minutes. The contractor reports that they placed the damaged pail in a 5 gallon over-pack and performed subsequent clean up.

column168: Veolia was offloading the Veolia straight truck with a forklift into the 10 day intransit Veolia facility when a drum that was already offloaded into the staging area was viewed to be leaking ink onto the floor. The Veolia trained employees quickly responded to the small pin sized hole in the 2nd chime on the drum from the bottom and tipped the drum onto its side to stop the leak. The drum was overpacked into a UN specification container and the spill material of ink was wiped up by employees and containerized. About 2-3 gallons of material was spilled onto the sealed floor of the facility, onto the asphalt loading dock area and truck floor. All material was cleaned up and properly disposed of.
column169: Train Veolia employees to be more aware of the drums when offloading them from the truck with a forklift. Look for signs of leaking or damaged drums. The damage was not caused by the forklift as it was discovered there was rust around the dented area of the leaking drum.

At about 11:10 am Kenneth Barefiel PHONE # 904-568-2363 from Federal Rail Administration came in to the Allied Jacksonville office. He asked David Schultz, Jacksonville Plant Manager, if rail car TILX110418, sitting outside of the Jacksonville facility fence, was Allied’s railcar (Jacksonville facility receiving the railcar). David answered yes. At this time per Mr. Barefiel’s instructions, both walked to the railcar to determine what was leaking from the railcar as Mr. Barefiel indicated he visually noted a leak. Upon arriving at the car that was presently stored on the rail road property, David also visually noted the leak as sodium hypochlorite was leaking from the top of the railcar. David instructed David Mason, Allied employee, to grab tools and then climb up the railcar to see what was leaking. David broke seal # 0002366 and visually inspected the railcar under the manway dome.  He noted that the three inch liquid line flange (product side) was leaking. Two of the bolts were determined to be finger loose and two were wrench tight. Using a wrench, David then tightened up the two loose bolts wrench tight as well as double checked the other two bolts to ensure they were tight. Upon immediately tightening the finger loose bolts, the sodium hypochlorite leak was mitigated.   David Schultz then called Ron Zeigler, Allied Regional Operations Manager, and reported the incident to him.   David Schultz then talked to Matthew Borchert from FEC (environmental compliance) office# 904-279-3277 cell# 904-600-2288 he said that since the rail car TILX110418 was still in there custody that FEC would take care of clean up.
column169: UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO BOLTS WERE FINGER LOOSE DIRECTLY RESULTING IN THE LOST OF BLEACH FROM THE RAILCAR.  EMPLOYEES WHO FAILED TO SECURE THE RAILCAR PROPERLY PRIOR TO RELEASE AND MOVEMENT ARE TO BE RETRAINED, AND DISCIPLINED ACCORDINGLY.  SENIOR MANAGEMENT WILL ALSO REVIEW COMPANY PROCEDURES TO DETERMINE IF FUTHER ENHANCEMENT OF THE PROCEDURE CAN BE MADE TO FURTHER PREVENT HUMAN ERROR AND OVERSIGHT.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: The incident occurred about 2-miles from the point of departure and involved a single commercial motor vehicle traveling northbound on River Road, a two-lane highway.  There were no injuries, but the vehicle was towed.   The roadway was closed for approximately 4-hours.    Based on evidence from the accident, and a witness statement, the driver apparently decided to stop the vehicle on the shoulder.  He planned on walking across the street to his personal vehicle which had broken down on his way to work, and was parked on the opposite side of the road roughly 50 feet from where the accident occurred.  The driver apparently slowed the vehicle (confirmed by the vehicle’s tracking system) to less than 10 mph, and pulled it partially onto the roadway’s shoulder which was 4-ft wide, but soft due to recent heavy rainfall.  The shoulder apparently gave away causing the vehicle to roll over to its passenger side.    9-1-1 was notified, and the carrier was also notified.  The carrier dispatched a spill responder to the scene due to the proximity to the Piscataquog River (roughly 1200 feet).  A tow truck uprighted the vehicle. Approximately 3-5 pounds of ammonium nitrate leaked from the cargo bin during the process of moving the vehicle to an upright position. The carrier also dispatched a crash specialist, who arrived that evening and investigated the accident the next morning.     The incident was determined to be caused by driver error, pulling off the hard roadway on to the shoulder.
column169: As a result of this accident, the carrier will do the following:    1. The driver's employment with the carrier was terminated.    2.  The carrier prepared and sent out an announcement to all of its terminals to be posted for 30 days, an alert concerning the incident/acciden and reminding all drivers of the dangers of moving a vehicle on the shoulder of rural roadways.    3. Austin Powder Company has an ongoing committment to the inclusion of rollover prevention as part of Smith System Training.

column168: On 7/15/2014 R&L Carriers reported that approximately 20 ounces of UN3378 Sodium Carbonate Peroxyhydrate "Green Clean Pro" was released to the concrete dock floor after a bag of the material was punctured by an apparent fork-lift. The punctured bag was over-packed and the released material was swept up and placed in a 5-gallon poly pail along with the PPE which was taken by the contractor for disposal.

Driver was scheduled to deliver to Customer. Customer requested samples of product from the bottom valve and also from the top of tanker. Driver retrieved sample from the unloading valve. After, he proceeded to top of tanker, opened the manway and retrieved the sample from the top of tanker. Driver closed dome lid but did not secure it with the hold downs. After some time, the receiving person at Customer advised that the sample had failed due to cloudiness and the load was being rejected. Driver called and advised the office of the rejected load. He was then instructed to return to the plant. Driver failed to secure the dome on top of tanker. Driver left the customer and approached the intersection of S. Creek and Amnicola where he had to stop for a red light. The light changed to green. As he turned onto Amnicola Hwy, he noticed the material out of his mirrors running down the side of tanker. He pulled to the side of the roadway and stopped. He called the Univar Chattanooga Dispatcher (Chris Frazier) and advised him of what happened. The Dispatcher advised me (Robby Brewer, Branch Operations Manager) of the spill.   I arrived as well as Chattanooga Fire Dept at which time the road was shut down. Marion Environmental was called for cleanup. The entire road was closed until 1200 and then half was opened to allow traffic to flow both directions with one lane instead of normal 2 lanes in each direction. Marion finished the cleanup around 1630.  The tanker was brought back to Univar and weighed for loss of material. The difference in the gross weights from when tanker was loaded and return to the plant was 200 pounds.

column168: ¿ Driver checked in with guard and was directed to unloading area.  ¿ Driver completed hookup and pressurized trailer.   ¿ No plant personal showed driver to unloaded area, driver checked around area and was unable to locate anyone.     ¿ Driver checked customer’s valve found it open. Valve is located behind retaining wall inside containment area where there appeared to be 3 to 4 inches of liquid covering hose inside of containment area.  ¿ Driver failed to check customer’s tank to determine the amount of room in customers tank if it could receive the amount product to be unloaded.    ¿ Driver began the unloading process prior to plant personal arrival.  ¿ Driver stood by the retaining wall at the beginning of the unload process and felt product was unloading without any issues.  ¿ Driver proceeded to his truck and entered the cab and was filling out paperwork during the unloading process.  ¿ One of the plant personal going by the unloading area observed fuming from within the containment area and notified driver product was being released.   ¿ Driver stopped the unloading process at that time, believed to be between 10 and 15 minutes from the time the unloading process had begun.  ¿ An undetermined amount of sulfuric acid was released into containment area.   ¿ The bleeder valve on the customer’s fill line located next to gate valve behind the retaining wall was found to be open. Allowing the product to be released into the containment area.    Customer handling clean-up.  The product was being used at that the time it was being offloaded.  Driver said there was 3-4" of water in the containment area when he arrived in an area spanning 50ft x 15 ft.  Customer advised that there was roughly 25 gallons.  At this time we are unclear on the amount that spilled into the containment area but 1200 gallons is on the high side.
column169: Factors:  ¿ Driver complacency.  ¿ Driver failed to follow Schneider’s and DuPont’s procedures and policies for unloading.  ¿ Valves left open at unloading site when driver arrived.  ¿ No plant personal present to assist driver.     Actions:  ¿ Driver permanently removed from DuPont acid business.  ¿ Driver will receive (PET) Performance Enhancement Training which is a post incident review and skills qaulification test at the end.  ¿ Driver will be placed on (CTE) Commitment To Excellence and a determination of driver’s future employment will be decided.    ¿ Driver’s performance bonus to be impacted.  ¿ DuPont work with USALCO to insure plant rules are in place and drivers are made aware of them upon arrival for all sulfuric acid loads being delivered into their plants.  ¿ DuPont work with USALCO to insure fail safes are in place.

column168: A random TAG Inspection for tariff compliance showed that container PAFX500960-0 on booking WB4808178 had UN1791 marked with the limited quantities markings on the package but no hazardous paperwork was provided to Horizon Lines, the containerized ocean carrier. column168: On July 18th, 2014 at 22:56 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered ADMX 30221, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car, coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Mercuria Energy Trading, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-07-18-00276. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the manway cover swing bolts 5 of 6 where less than tool tight, causing a release of product between the manway cover gasket and the nozzle, the gasket was inspected, found to be deteriorated and was replaced, the tank car was wiped down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Tim Holan, Rail Logistics Manager, Cell: 832-993-7537 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. ADMX 30221 was released for transport.    This incident did NOT require a special move.    Cause Code: 200 (5 points) and 209 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On July 21, 2014 at 11:03 hours personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard discovered UTLX 14991, a loaded tank car of Phosphoric Acid Solution, leaking from the bottom of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2014-0721-00096.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve mounting flange bolts were less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Virgil Fowler 706-469-1301.  Contractor personnel attempted to tighten the flange bolts; however, this did not stop the release.  The product from the leaking tank car was transferred into an empty tank car and the spill area remediated.  This did require a special switching move.     NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32  Cause Code: 535

column168: On July 21st, 2014 at 07:05 hours, personnel at the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered ACFX 76591, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car coming from around the manway. column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. vehicle transported a hazardous waste load from multiple customer locations to the Clean Harbors Clackamas, OR facility. column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver has been re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container closure and gasket integrity before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before loading and transportation is initiated. column168: On July 29, 2014 at 15:15 hours personnel in the CSXT Corbin Yard detected an odor from train Q54227.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to inspect the cars in the train. column168: 12:00 am    OUR DRIVER WAS GOING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 8, MILE MARKER 18 HEADING O HIS DELIVERY SITE IN ABERDEEN, WA AND THE TRACTOR BEGAN TO OVERHEAT. OUR DRIVER BEGAN PULLING OVER TO THE SHOULDER AND THE ENGINE DIED. HE WAS STILL TRAVELING ABOUT 40 MPH AND HAD LOST POWER STEERING ABILITY. ONCE POWER STEERING IS LOST EVEN THE SMALLEST CORRECTION OF STEERING IS NOT POSSIBLE. THE TRUCK WAS ALMOST COMPLETELY STOPPED; IT TIPPED SIDEWAYS 30 DEGREES OR SO INTO THE DITCH AND RESTED ON THE SIDE OF THE MOUNTAIN. THE AREA IS DIRT FILL AND ROCKS; COMPARTMENT ONE IN THE TRACTOR WAS PUNCTURED BY A SHARP ROCK EDGE WHEN THE TRACTOR CAME TO REST AND FUEL BEGAN SPILLING PUT IN THE DITCH. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK DUE TO THE SIZE OF THE HOLE AND THE ANGLE OF THE TRACTOR AGAINST THE MOUNTAIN.    OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OUR CENTRAL DISPATCH OFFICE, AND EMERGENCY RESPONDER CREW (AREA MANAGER, FIELD SAFETY SUPERVISOR, AND FLEET MANAGER); RESPONDER CREW NOTIFIED WA STATE PATROL, WADEQ AND NRC. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE RADIATOR HOSE HAD BURST CAUSING THE ENGINE TO OVERHEAT THIS THE ENGINE PROTECTION SHUTDOWN ACTIVATED AND STOPPED THE ENGINE.    1:21am    OUR FLEET MANAGER REPORTED THERE WAS 2-4000 GALLONS OF UNL FUEL ON THE GROUND; FROM, COMPARTMENT ONE OF THE TRACTOR.  THE FUEL HAD DISSIPATED IN APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES.    THE REMAINING FUEL IN THE TRACTOR WAS PUMPED OFF; NISQUALLY TOW REMOVED THE TRACTOR ROM THE DITCH.    7:00am JULY 11. 2014    NRC AND EPI MET OUR CREW AT THE SITE TO TEST AND DETERMINE THE PLAN OF ACTION RECOVERY OF ANY FREE PRODUCT AND CLEANUP OF THE ENVIRONMENT.    AS OF TODAY, JULY 23, 2014 NRC AND EPI ARE WORKING HAND IN HAND WITH WADOT TO CLEANUP THE CONTAMINATED AREA AS REQUIRED BY STATE AND LOCAL JURISDICTION.
column169: INCLUDE MORE THOROUGH PRE TRIP INSPECTION OF HOSES TO IDENTIFY WORN HOSES IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT. THE MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT WILL GO THROUGH ALL TRUCKS IN THE FLEET AND DOUBLE CHECK AND REPLACE ANY WARN HOSES.

A driver had picked up a shipment of hazardous waste and was headed to the intermediate truck transfer facility when he hit his brakes hard to avoid a collision.  When doing so, a drum slid forward into the pallet jack on the truck, puncturing it.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leaking drum was overpacked into a salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to clean the trailer floor and the small amount that leaked onto the ground.  Louisiana State police were called but did not respond...incident number 14-03302.
column169: The driver was issued a written warning for failure to adequately block and brace the load to insure against movement in such a situation.  He also received re-training in proper load securement.

column168: A driver arrived at the intended disposal facility with a tanker trailer loaded with hazardous waste.  During a routine inspection, a small amount of liquid was noticed to be leaking down the side of the trailer from the dome lid.  The driver checked the tightness of the dome lid and they were all tight.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned the material from the side of the trailer with a suitable absorbent material.  The trailer was parked in the sample rack overnight and the next morning had not leaked further and was accepted into the disposal facility.
column169: The tanker was not leaking at the time of pickup.  When it was emptied, it was taken out of service to the maintenance facility for replacement of the dome lid gasket.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: During transportation of 3 X 55 gallon stainless steel drums Containing Nitric Acid one gasket failed on a 3/4 inch bung. The gasket appeared to have cracked during transportation allowing vapors to escape into the trailer. Some moisture was evident on the top of the drum around the 3/4 inch bung estimated as less than one liquid oz.     When the driver arrived at the customer dock and opened the trailer door to unload, vapors from the drum had caused the trailer to have a smokey appearance. As the customer did not have it's own in house Emergency Response Team they called for emergency response from the local fire department. As a precautionary measure the warehouse and production area of the plant was evacuated. When emergency response workers from the Haz Mat team entered the rear of the trailer they observed that one of the bung gaskets had failed causing the release of vapors into the trailer. The gasket was replaced on site.
column169: Gaskets will be inspected prior to loading trailers. Also, drivers have been instructed whenever possible and when it is safe to do so (depending on the load configuration) all drums should be checked at each stop to ensure they are in good order.

column168: On Wednesday 7/9 at approximately 14:10 hrs, the TRANSFLO - Cincinnati terminal personnel were in the process of conducting a tanker trailer (MC 312) to tank car (DOT 111) transfer of 45,000 lbs of Spent Sulfuric Acid (UN 1832, Class 8, PG II) on behalf of Shipper DUPONT E I DENEMOURS and their customer Pilot Chemical 3439 Yankee Road Middletown, OH 45044.  The transfer was initiated from originating Quality Carriers trailer # 7150 (rear) and into receiving tank car UTLX 14238 (top) utilizing compressed air, and water based vapor return scrubber system (Unit # BP 2204).  This was the first transfer into tank car UTLX 14238, as the residue/empty car arrived and was spotted at the terminal back on 7/3 located on track #5.  Within a minute of starting the transfer, the transfer operator detected a very heavy odor of spent acid in the area.  The Operator began tracing his line and ensuring no leak was occurring at the hose/fitting connection points; he then discovered that a small stream of acid was squirting out of the bottom of the car from a broken weld where a former sump.  The Operator notified office personnel of the spill and other personnel responded to the incident scene with spill containment supplies (sand; absorbent).  Terminal personnel then deployed spill pans under the stream and gathered some buckets and more spill pans to capture as much of the product as possible.  By 14:40 hrs Terminal personnel made notifications of said incident to TRANSFLO, Savage and DuPont along with dispatching a hazmat/environmental response crews (Pettit Environmental; EMS) to remediate the area and stop the tank car leakage.  Notifications were also made to the NRC Report # 1088628, Chemtrec Report # 2014070900249, Ohio EPA Report # 1407-31-1411
column169: DuPont shall be applying for and have to be granted a OTMA-1, prior to the UTLX 14238 being sent to a tank car repair shop, where it can be throughly cleaned, inspected and repaired.  Once the car is shopped will a cause be properly identified and corresponding corrective action plan instituted.

column42: CARBAMATE PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, FLASH POINT NOT LESS THAN 23 DEGREES C
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: At 0355 ET hours, Mike Hart of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding a release of approximately 5 gallons of a UN2991 CARBAMATE PESTICIDE LIQUID TOXIC FLAMMABLE liquid to the floor and undercarriage of a trailer and adjacent parking pad at the Ellenwood, GA terminal. At the time of this report, no soils, drains or waterways were reported as being impacted. ERTS will make any appropriate regulatory reporting if necessary and post those updates. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL and MSDS. The shipper is Dupont. ERTS will make the Chemtrec notification as required by client. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate 120 minute ETA to site.ERTS notified Chemtrec : Bob Wible acknowledged the incident and issued # 2014-07-31-00024.The contractor reports locating 1-2.5 gallon pail that has been punctured by wooden splinters from wood from the trailer running board resulting in the release. An approximate area 3ft x 1 ft on the trailer floor was impacted along with 6 boxes being heavily stained by the released product. Clean up operations are on going. The contractor will decontaminate all impacted cargo and repack the skid accordingly.

It was reported approximately four ounces of product has been release from two 275-gallon totes due to missing caps. The released material impacted the metal frame around the tote causing deterioration of the metal. The product dried and no cleanup was necessary. However, ERTS scheduled Morgan Environmental to conduct a product transfer.

column168: At approx 1 PM the driver was heading north on rt 53 in Wilmington il. Heattempted to turn left and head west to I-55. Approx half way through the turn he heard a pop coming from the box. He then felt an impact in the side wall of the box on the passenger side. The momentum of the truck, and the impact of the tote put him on his side. He was able to release the seat belt and kick out the windshield. He  evaluated the box and noticed a small but constant flow of 20 percent caustic coming from the box. He immediately called a tow company, 911, and company manager . The company manager forwarded the number to 3rd party spill response.    3rd Party environmental cleanup company arrived at approx 5:45 PM. Product transfer and cleanup was begun.

column168: Driver noticed a leak and pulled over on the northbound exit ramp to I35 at exit 45. Local authorities had driver move to Ritchie Brothers Facility.  Leak appeared to be from a valve area under the back of the trailer.  Load was transferred to another trailer without further incident.  Approximately 95 gallons of product leaked out but contained. Environmental contractor hired to clean-up and remediate the scene.  Trailer was internally washed and returned to St. Louis for inspection.
column169: It was determined that the upper internal mounting flange gasket that bolts to the sump had failed.  The gasket was a standard Teflon material.  No defects were found  in the valve mounting surfaces, sump or mounting stud cavities or valve.  Both the upper and lower gaskets were replaced with solid gylon gaskets, pressure tested and trailer returned to service.    This is the first time we have had a gasket failure such as this.  On future leak and pressure testing, all valve flange gaskets will be visually inspected for defects or signs of leakage.

column168: At 1420 est, Shannon Klimek, with Schneider National notified ERTS of a trailer that has a liquid inside it, the released chemical UN2468, Trichloroisocyanuric Acid, Dry, Class 5.1, PG II. Terminal safety personnel is estimating the release to be approximately 2 gallons in size.  This material is hygroscopic (absorbs moisture from the air), the original release was a powder but by the time of discovery it had turned into a liquid.  The size of the release was about 3"x48' and was confined to the inside of the trailer. An ERTS network contractor was notifed and has a 45 minute eta and has been provided with an SDS and also requested to take ph paper to test the liquid, as per the MSDS the ph for this material is 3. Ph readings in the front of the trailer was 3.5 and at the rear of the trailer was 4.5.  There was no impact to water ways, drains, or parking area.

column168: On July 24, 2014 at 15:39 ET, approximately 20 gallons from a 55-gallon poly drum containing UN1993 Flammable Liquids released inside of a Landstar trailer (688837) on I-90 Eastbound near mile-marker 19 in St. Reggis, MT (Mineral County). The release impacted the trailer floor, asphalt below and gravel soil shoulder. The release was caused by an apparent load shift while in transit which caused one 55-gallon drum to drop on its side caused a leak from the closure cap. The entire release was cleaned up and containerized for proper disposal.

Clean Harbors employee was removing 6x1 liter plastic bottles from the customer store when 1 of the bottles accidently fell on the pavement causing the cap to crack which released approximately 12-15 ounces of acidic material.  The spill was immediately cleaned up, the damaged cap was replaced on the contained, the container was placed inside a secondary container and both the container and the clean up material was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: The Clean Harbors employee was required to review the SOP on the use of secondary containment while moving hazardous materials.

column168: NCR 119580    Root Cause: Eagle trailer 4803 was leaking MIBK from compartment # 5 coming from the shell of the tank near the trailer tandems.     Investigation:  Trailer 4803 had just loaded at Eastman and the driver had come by the terminal for the shop to look at a tire on the trailer.  While the shop was looking at the tire, they noticed a small drip of liquid was dripping from the underneath the tank near the axle.  The drip was about 10-15 seconds per drop.  The product was MIBK which evaporates almost immediately.  They immediately placed a bucket underneath the leak to capture it from hitting the ground.  The product evaporated as soon as it hit the bucket due to the leak being so little.  The shop notified Jaime in dispatch and she immediately called Eastman Fire Department.  They came over to investigate and evaluated by the Fire Captain that the trailer would be safe to move back to the plant so they could unload number 5 compartment on this tank.  Once the compartment was empty at Eastman, we were instructed to clean that compartment and deliver the other 4 compartments of product to the customer in New Jersey on 8/31.  The tank was pulled from service as soon as it returned to Kingsport.  It was then cleaned and sent to Polar Service Center for them to investigate the cause of the leak.    Polar Service Center discovered small crack in the barrel located in front of the tandem where the channel ring jumps across the heater panel.  This is the highest stress area on a tank trailer due to the twisting and turning.  This is very common in compartment trailers regardless of the make and year it was manufactured.
column169: Action taken to prevent reoccurrence:  The trailer is still in the shop being repaired.  They are lifting #2, #3 & #4 jacket sheets from the rear, the outriggers on either side of the channel ring at front of tandem.  Then remove the air tanks for access and remove section of belly pan, remove cross member and section of channel ring and pad, repair cracks in shell and install a 14 gauge pad over heater panel.  This pad will be 3 inches longer than pad when it was manufactured.  They will then install new cross member and 2 outriggers.    Then to spread the stress on this area, the following items are also being completed.  The area between #2 and #3 rings from rear above tandem sub frame needs to be enclosed.  The section, they will install laps the tubular frame on the outside and runs up and at the top where there is a bend or approximately 45 degrees to reduce the stress where it is welded to the vessel.  These are skip welded at 4” on 4” all the way around on each side of the tandem frame.    Polar Service Center in Spartanburg has been doing this type of repair for 4 years and have not had any units returned for repairs for this section of the tank.

A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Services,Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. The vehicle was staged and upon movement, approximately 10 gallons spilled from tank trailer to containment area.  Driver stopped immediately and the began the cleanup process.  All material was cleaned and the equipment secured.
column169: In order to prevent recurrence; all plant personnel and drivers at this location have been retrained in securing equipment prior to moving it.  In addition, management team wll also go through retraining in order that they may assist drivers with maintaining compliance.

column168: A R&L Carriers terminal located in Antioch, TN found a damaged 330-gallon plastic tote during unloading. Approximately 4 oz. of UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide material was released from the tote onto the trailer floor due to a stress crack. To mitigate this release, a contractor (B&P Ent) was dispatched in order to transfer the remaining material into a new 330-gallon plastic tote, and the clean the small impacted area inside of the trailer. The new tote was properly labeled for continued transportation.

On July 25, 2014, Ruan Transport notified ERTS of a release of approximately 10 gallons of Sodium Bisulfite, UN2693, Class 8, PG III. The release was from trailer #R81003 and occurred when the rear cap was removed and approximately 10 gallons of Sodium Bisulfite was in the piping and was released onto asphalt. ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site for cleanup activities.

It was reported that a leak was coming from the trailer and dripping onto the trailer's tire. ERTS dispatched a contractor for initial response and cleanup activities.

column168: ERTS was notified at 1812 est of a release of UN2810, Toxic Liquids, Organic, n.o.s. there is currently approximately 2 gallons that have impacted the gravel lot under the trailer. There are no drains or water ways impacted at this time. This release was noticed at 1800 est.  There were a total of 17 totes in this trailer. The contractor indicated that the released material is ~ 1 gallon and is a result of the totes being over filled and that one of the totes lid was unsecured resulting in the release. The contractor is cleaning up the minimal release from the tops of the 4' by 4' totes and containerize the waste for pending disposal. The contractor will secure all 17 totes to ensure the are DOT roadworthy.

I CONTAINED THE SPILL, AND THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS RETURNED TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER FOR FURTHER PROCESSING IN THE DMP. ON ARRIVAL IN THE DMP, AND IMMEDIATELY UPON THE INITIAL STAGES OF DAMAGED MATERIAL PROCESSING, THE PACKAGE WAS OBSERVED EMITTING AN IRRITATING ODOR. AS THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE SOLIDS AND LIQUIDS INDICATED THE USE OF AN SCBA IN THE EVENT OF IRRITATED ODORS, AND SINCE THIS FACILITY IS NOT EQUIPPED WITH SCBA, AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS CONTACTED FOR REMOVAL OF THE DAMAGED PACKAGE, ITS CONTENTS AND ASSOCIATED DEBRIS

column168: A PeroxyChem Driver was hauling a load of 50% Hydrogen Peroxide to our customer.  He was traveling North in the inside lane of the 1170 block of SH 146.  A service body truck was slightly ahead of the our tractor trailer in the outside lane.  The other vehicle decided to make an unsafe U-turn, which was in front of our tractor/trailer.    PeroxyChem driver swerved to try to avoid the vehicle, but was unable to avoid hitting the other vehicle on its' side. PeroxyChem tractor/trailer ended up swerving into a ditch on other side of the road. As the vehicle rolled over, the cab struck a telephone/utility pole. Law enforcement arrived on-scene and shut down both sides of Hwy 146. Other response agencies also arrived. The hydrogen peroxide slowly leaked out the trailer vent assembly until the trailer was uprighted late in the evening. After re-scaling the trailer it was determined 198 gallons were released.     PeroxyChem Driver had to be cut out of the cab by the Mont Belvieu Fire Department (MBFD). PeroxyChem driver was taken by ambulance to a local hospital, and was subsequently released a short while later. The driver of the other vehicle appeared to be unharmed.  The other vehicle driver received a citation for "Turned When Unsafe".  PeroxyChem Pasadena personnel responded.
column169: Due to the fact the incident was cased by an unsafe action by the other vehicle driver (Unsfae U-Turn directly in front of our tractor trailer) for which he received a citation from the police officer we do not have any recommendations at this time.

column168: Shipment was picked up as NA3077 Hazardous waste solid.  The driver did not see any leaking material when picked up.  The shipment was unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility and not leaking at that time.  The next morning it was noticed that a drum had leaked approximately 6 ounces of liquid onto the concrete dock floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and transfered the material into drums that were rated for this material, which was a liquid.  The shipment was mis-described by the generator and should have been UN1760.  The shipment, along with the material used to clean up the spill was loaded onto a van trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipper was notified that the material was not as described by them when picking up and therefore was not placed into drums rated for that material.  They will be handling the matter internally.

column168: At approximately 8:34am, a release of approximately 334 gallons of Vinyl Acetate Monomer (UN 1301; Class 3 - Flammable; PG II), for shipper CELANESE Ltd, occurred at the Charlotte East terminal during a tank car (CELX 23036) to tanker trailer (Tidewater Transit Trailer #1192) transfer utilizing 3" Platform Pump PLP 2135 with meter and vapor balance.  The release occurred via the rear discharge valve of TWT trailer #1192.  Operator Philip Darby failed to identify that the trailer's rear valve was not closed or capped during the truck/trailer inspection, following the trailer wash.  Terminal personnel attempted to dam and dike the immediate area, but approximately 20 gallons of product escaped over the berm located on the east side of track 9 and impacted the ground on the property directly adjacent to the terminal.  The Charlotte Fire Department was called and responded as a precaution.  EMS and representatives from Mecklenburg County also responded to the scene following the release.  Carolina Environment Response Team (CRT) arrived and cleaned up the area of the spill located on the asphalt. They filled six 55-gallon drums with absorbent material used to soak up the VAM and left the site. SWS Environmental Services was than dispatched by TRANSFLO to finalize the clean up effort. SWS excavated the affected soil and filled two 20 yard roll-off containers which are currently located onsite. The 6 55-gallon drums filled by CRT were dumped into the roll off containers for disposal. The clean up was completed at 6:00pm and the gathered material profiled/manifested for disposal.  No storm drains were impacted as the Gate Valve was immediately closed once the release was realized.
column169: The involved operator was disciplined via two day suspension and a coaching counseling/re-training session was conducted where a commitment was obtained to ensure that trailers are thoroughly inspected prior to initiating a transfer, by walking around the entire transport and ensuring that vehicle is roadworthy, clean dry odor free or previous contents compatible with the scheduled transfer, can safely contain the lading and all valves and outlets are closed and capped. This was completed on 7/29/14.

column168: R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to report the release of 6 ounces of UN1760, Corrosive Liquids, N.O.S., 8, PG II.onto the trailer floor and a approximate 2' x 2'gravel area in the rail yard. One five gallon bucket had a small hole due to an apparent freight shift. The location of the release was at a Union Pacific rail Brooklyn yard at the intersection of SE 19th Ave and Holgate Blvd, Portland, OR. It was reported that the driver noticed the trailer was leaking an unknown material. He notified rail yard personnel who moved the trailer to the containment area. The impacted bucket was placed into an over pack and one 30-gallon drum of waste was generated and taken off-site for disposal.

Dana Transportation contacted ERTS at 11:55 EST to dispatch a contractor to handle clean-up activities on Trailer 1065 at Sal-Ave Yard 31495 South Unitech Dr. Laredo, TX. It was reported that the tanker had a leak from a possible crack and a temperature gauge seal leaking. Tanker had UN2280 Hexamethylenediamine originally in it but it has been transferred out. Outside of tanker had evidence of corrosion on it from material and a 2' x 2' area of gravel was impacted. All impacted areas of tanker were scrapped cleaned, the 2'x 2' area of gravel was hand excavated. Contractor reported that the temperature gauge was cracked which caused the release. One 55 gallon poly drum was generated and taken by contractor for disposal.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Following offload at customer location, a hose backflow occurred, which resulted in the loss of approximately 600 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution from the customer's tank. The free product released to the asphalt surface, adjacent soils, and entered into a storm drain onsite. Trans Environmental of Loves Park, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Stockton Cheese personnel proceeded to flush the lines, to prevent migration. Trans Environmental used absorbent material on the free product, secured the area, and coordinated excavation of impacted soils. Trans Environmental returned to the site, excavated impacted soils, and pulled samples from impacted area to confirm no further contamination remained. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

OUR DRIVER EXITED I90 AT HAMPSHIRE, IL (ROUTE 20) TO GET FUEL AT PETRO TRUCK STOP.  SOMEONE (?) CONTACTED THE HAMPSHIRE (IL) POLICE DEPT NOTICED SOME PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. THE FIRE DEPT WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED. THE HAMPSHIRE SAID 3-4 GALS LEAKED OUT FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. WE SENT OUR MECHANIC OUT TO THE SCENE TO INSPECT THE TRAILER. HE DISCOVERED ONE OF THE THREE EARS OF THE REAR PORT ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS OVERTIGHTENED, MAKING THE LID NOT SIT FLUSH. HE RESECURED THE CLEAN OUT PORT TIGHTENING IT DOWN EVENLY. SO IT WAS FLSUH WITH TRAILER. THE FIRE DEPT. STAYED WITH THE TRAILER UNTIL THE REPARIS WERE COMPLETED TO TRAVEL AGAIN. THE EPA WAS NOTIFIED AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR CAME OUT TO DO THE CLEAN UP.
column169: BECAUSE THE REAR PORT WAS NOT SEATED CORRECTLY, THERE WAS A GAP ALLOWING SOME PRODUCT TO ESCAPE ALONG THE SIDE OF THE TANK. UPON THE RETURN OF THE TANK TO OUR TERMINAL, IT WAS SENT TO OUR REPAIR SHOP, WHERE A REPLACEMENT GASKET WAS INSTALLED. THE TRAILER WAS PRESSURE TESTED AND HELD PRESSURE.

CDT, A DRIVER OF A TRACTOR TANKER OPERATED BY SOLAR TRANSPORT WAS OFF LOADING FUEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK WHEN IT WAS ACCIDENTALLY OVERFILLED. APPROX 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. THE SPILLLED FUEL WAS WITHIN THE CONCRETE AND GRAVEL CONTAINMENT BERM.

column168: TRACTOR TRAILER WAS TAKING A LEFT TURN (WEST) FROM NORTHBOUND HIGHWAY 85 ONTO WELD COUNTY ROAD (WCR) 141/2 AND WAS STRUCK IN THE REAR PORTION OF THE TRAILER BY A DIRT HAULING TRUCK GOING SOUTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 85. THE TRAILER OVERTURNED AND ONE COMPARTMENT RUPTURED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE REMAINING FUEL WAS RECOVERED FOLLOWING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CUTTING HOLES IN THE TRAILER AND HAVING THE FUEL PUMPED ONTO A BOBTAIL TRUCK. SOUTHBOUND HIGHWAY 85 AND WCR 14 1/2 WERE CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS WHILE THE IMPACTS TO THE ROADWAY WERE MITIGATED AND THE TRUCKS WERE REMOVED. ADDITIONAL IMPACTS OCCURRED WHEN DIESEL FLOWED OFF THE ROADWAY AND ONTO COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (CDOT) PROPERTY ADJACENT TO HIGHWAY 85. FOLLOWING ASCERTAINING A PERMIT FROM CDOT, SOIL EXCAVATION WAS CONDUCTED AND FOLLOWING THE REMOVAL OF APPROXIMATELY 530CUBIC YARDS OF SOILS, ANALYTICAL RESULTS INDICATE THE REMEDIAL EFFORTS SHOULD BE COMPLETE.
column169: The cause and responsible party to the accident remains under investigation.

column168: THE UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS ONE CARTON CONTAINING ID8000, CONSUMER COMMODITY, CLASS 9 THAT WAS TENDERED TO ALASKA AIRLINES AS PART OF A 19 LOT. THE PACKAGE WAS MARKED WITH A LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK. INSIDE THE CARTON WERE SIX CANVAS KITS, EACH CONTAINING ONE AEROSOL CANISTER CONTAINING 133 ML OF ID8000. THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO ALASKA AIRLINES IN NEWARK, NJ, AND ARRIVED IN FAIRBANKS, AK ON ALASKA FLIGHT 123 ON JULY 8, 2014. THE ALASKA MASTER AIR WAYBILL NUMBER WAS 027-11578626. EXPEDITERS INTERNATIONAL OF WASHINGTON TENDERED THE SHIPMENT TO ALASKA AIRLINES AS THE FREIGHT FORWARDER ON EXPEDITERS' MASTER REFERENCE EWRT037832, HOUSE BILL REFERENCEH280047117. THE CARGO ON HOUSE BILL H280047117 WAS TENDERED TO EXPEDITERS BY TRIANGLE DISTRIBUTION ON BEHALF OF AMERICAN EAGLE OUTFITTERS AS PART OF AN 11 LOT WEIGHING 101 POUNDS TOTAL. BECAUSE OTHER CONSIGNMENTS WERE SHIPPED AT THE SAME TIME, IN TOTAL 62 CARTONS WERE SHIPPED ON PALLETS. TRIANGLE TENDERED THE GOODS AS "APPAREL/MERCHANDISE," AND DID NOT DECLARE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. SINCE AN APPAREL SHIPMENT DID NOT REQUIRE IT, JV TRANSPORTATION DISPATCHED A DRIVER WITH NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRAINING TO PICKUP THE GOODS. FOR THIS REASON, AND THE FACT THAT THE CARGO WAS ON PALLETS, THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTE THE LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK. THE CARGO WAS NOT RECEIVED IN EXPEDITERS' WAREHOUSE, BUT WAS TENDERED DIRECTLY TO ALASKA AIRLINES IN NEWARK BY JV TRANSPORTATION ON BEHALF OF EXPEDITORS. BECAUSE CARGO WAS AT NO TIME IN THE DIRECT POSSESSION OF EXPEDITERS, IT WAS NOT POSSIBLE FOR EXPEDITORS TO SEE THE LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK ON THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE ANCHORAGE CARGO HANDLING FACILITY BY ALASKA AIRLINES PERSONNEL. THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE OR UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
column169: AMERICAN EAGLE HAS DISCUSSED THIS UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT INTERNALLY, AND WILL CONDUCT A DANGEROUS GOODS MEETING WITH ITS DEPARTMENT HEADS OF SUPPLY CHAIN TO DISCUSS FUTURE SHIPPING NEEDS, AND DEVELOP A PLAN FOR CLASS 9 MATERIAL AS IT PERTAINS TO DIRECT TO STORE SHIPPING FROM TRANSLOADING FACILITIES SUCH AS TRIANGLE DISTRIBUTION. AMERICAN EAGLE HAS ALSO COMMUNICATED TO TRIANGLE THAT THEY MUST OBTAIN PROPER DANGEROUS GOODS CERTIFICATION TO SHIP DANGEROUS GOODS. JV TRANSPORTATION, THE TRUCKING COMPANY THAT MOVED THE SHIPMENT FROM TRIANGLE TO THE NEWARK AIRPORT HAS REVIEWED THIS ISSUE WITH ITS OPERATIONS MANAGERS. IT WILL INCLUDE DISCUSSIONS OF THE LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK IN ITS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND DOCK HANDLING TRAINING.

column168: THE CONSIGNEE DISCOVERED A MATERIAL LEAKING FROM TWO DRUMS DURING UNLOADING OF THE TRAILER.  THE CON-WAY DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND REPORTED TO THE INCIDENT.  THE CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT CALLED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (TEAM) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  THE TEAM ENTERED THE TRAILER AND FOUND THE TWO DRUMS HAD BEEN MOVED TO THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER AND THE REMAINING DRUMS HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TEAM INVERTED THE DRUMS INTO 95 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM.  THE TEAM INSPECTED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS AND FOUND SMALL CRACKS IN THE STEEL BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS HAD CAUSED THE LEAKAGE.  THERE WERE TWO WHITE SPOTS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WHERE THE DRUM HAD LEAKED.  ONE WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE FOOT IN DIAMETER, THE OTHER WAS APPROXIMATELY 4 X 6 INCHES.  THE TEAM USED CLAY ABSORBENTS TO REMOVE AS MUCH OF THE STAINING AS POSSIBLE.  THE ABSORBENTS AND A CONTAMINATED PALLET WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON WASTE DRUM AND LABELED.  THE TWO DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPACKAGING.  THE WASTE DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE EQ FACILITY IN TAMPA, FL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  NO FURTHER ACTION IS REQUIRED.

column168: Driver made connections to customer tank. As soon as the internal valve was opened sending product to the pump it began to leak from the weep whole in the pump seal. The internal valve was closed immediately along with a 3"valve leading to the liquid pump leaving a small amount of ammonia liquid in the piping and pump that bleed out through the leaking pump seal. The drivers quick action in closing the internal valve limited the leak to the small amount in the piping and pump.

column168: THE KAG WEST, LLC DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON I-5 NEAT MONTEREY PARK, CALIFORNIA WHEN ASPHALT BEGAN TO BE RELEASED FROM AN OPEN DOME LID ON THE TRAILER. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF ASPHALT WAS SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE CALIFORIA DOT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KAG WEST, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: THE TRANPSORT SERVICE, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 59 NEAR CLEVELAND, TEXAS WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED FIRE COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND NOTIFIED EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. DUE TO THE INTENSE HEAT, THE SEALS ON THE DISCHARGE VLAVES WERE COMPROMISED AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF STYRENE MONOMER WHEN THE PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK TRAILER. MASTERS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ALREADY ON SCENE TO ASSIST WITH THE PRODUCT TRANSFER AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMETNAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC WILL COMPLETE AN INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE FIRE AND MAKE ANY NECESSARY REPAIRS IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

column168: VEHICLE ACCIDENT ON THE SIDE OF ROAD RESULTED IN MINIMAL RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM DISPATCHED AND DRUM PLACED INTO LINED SALVAGE DRUM TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. SPILLAGE ABSORBED AND CLEANED UP PROPERLY WITH DISPOSAL.
column169: THIS WAS CAUSED BY ANOTHER TRUCKING COMPANY SO LIABILITY/LEGAL DEPARTMENTS WILL MAKE THE RECOMMENDATIONS.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: AT APPROX 5 AM ON 7/4/14 OUR DRIVER VEERED ON TO THE LEFT HAND SHOULDER OF THE LEFT  EASTBOUND LANE OF I-10. HE THEN OVER CORRECTED TO THE RIGHT. HIS LOAD BEGAN TO SLOSH BACK AND FORTH IN THE TRAILER CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE. THE VEHICLE THEN ROLLED ON TO THE DRIVERSIDE AND SLID APPROX 300 FT. COMING TO REST ACROSS BOTH LANES OF THE EASTBOUND SIDE OF I-10. AS THE TANK SLID ALONG THE PAVEMENT THE PAVEMENT RIPPED IN THE SKIN OF THE TANK. THE RIP WAS AGAINST THE PAVEMENT WHEN THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST SO THE LEAK COULD NOT BE PLUGGED AT THAT TIME. A BERM WAS BUILT IN THE CENTER MEDIAN SO THE PRODUCT WOULD NOT TRAVEL. SWS WAS BROUGHT IN TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANK AND TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION.
column169: TIDEPORT CONDUCTED REMEDIAL TRAINING ON "ROLLOVER PREVENTION" AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING THAT INCLUDED THE VIDEO "ROLLOVER" BY FMCSA.

column168: BEI HAWAII WAS EXECUTING A LEFT TURN AFTER A COMPLETE STOP FROM HI-56N ONTO HWY 583 MA'ALO RD WHEN THE METAL HOOK ON THE STRAP HOLDING DOWN 2 TOTE BINS BROKE. THIS CAUSED THE TOTES ON THE TRAILER TO BECOME LOOSE. THE TWO TOTES SLID OFF THE TRAILER BED ONTO THE HIGHWAY. THE TOTES CONTAINED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE AND 350 GALLONS (3,570LBS) OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 3 MINUTES. THE RELEASE WAS MITIGATED USING ANHYDROUS SODIUM SULFATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE AND ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED. THE RELEASE AND MATERIAL IN CLEANUP WAS SCOOPED UP AND SENT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. 911 WAS CALLED ALONG WITH NRC AND THE KAUAI FIRE DEPT/HAZMAT WAS ON SCENE.
column169: CHECKING AND REPLACING STRAPS MORE FREQUENTLY

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING DIESEL TO A FARM LOCATION THAT HAD 4 SEPARATE TANKS. GUAGES WERE NOT MARKED AS WELL AS COULD BE. DRIVER PICKED TANK WITH LEAST AMOUNT INDICATED AND THOUGHT ALL WOULD FIT INTO THE BULK TANK. THE FUEL STARTED TO COME OUT THE TOP VENT AS HE WAS NEARING THE END OF HIS DELIVERY. THE FUEL WAS SPILLED INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA SURROUNDING THE TANKS. CONTRACTOR WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED TO REMOVE THE FUEL FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE WAS COMPLETED BY 1800 THE FOLLOWING DAY.
column169: THE TANKS HAVE BEEN MARKED BETTER AND INSTRUCTIONS FOR THE GUAGES HAVE BEEN EXPLAINED TO THE DRIVER AND DISPATCH TO AVOID THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: Container HLXU 303832 was discovered leaking an estimated (1) gallon of a water-like substance in the Dupo, IL Rail Yard. Upon inspection it was found that moisture had been trapped inside the container causing a reaction with a torn bag of a sodium hydroxide, solid product. As a result the container was adjusted and dried of any moisture.
column169: Ensure that contianer is dried of any moisture prior to transportation. In addition provide buffer material bewteen double stacked pallets to avoid torn and crushed product.

column63: UN1203, GASOLINE, 3 PG II/1 CARGO TANK
column168: Truck #249 was traveling North on 115 @ 0515 a passenger car (blk KIA) sideswiped our unit on the driver side steer tire. This caused our unit to be pushed to the right into the soft dirt shoulder of the roadway. The driver could not recover at this point causing him to roll over onto the units top. The truck and trailer came to rest over a concrete v ditch that caught all of the oil from the truck and the amount that was released from the trailer. The truck tank had no release of product. The trailer was holding until 4 hours into the accident when a small amount started to leak on to the ground through the pressure vent near the dome. This release continued until the product was completely pumped out of the unit. The product that leaked onto the concrete ditch was diked and vacuumed by an outside company. All dirt that was contaminated was picked up and hauled away in labeled barrels. The concrete that had fuel released onto it was steam cleaned and vacuumed up as well.
column169: We have made it mandatory that all drivers must drive with two hands on the wheel at all times. The Beall manufactured tank that was involved in this accident held up very well. We as a company would like to see Federal D.O.T require a lower center of gravity cargo tank with no more than the required free space outage for the commodity carried.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver was entering a construction zone and did not see traffic slowing down. The driver swerved to avoid the vehicles that slowed down in front of him and in doing so rolled the truck over. The vessel didn't rupture or leak from the rollover. The spill was caused when the fuel was extracted from the vessel so that that it could be uprighted. A local HAZ-MAT team as well as the owner of the company were called out to the site to help manage the clean up.
column169: Driver was provided with additional training on entering construction zones, and seeing hazards on the road around him.

column168: Our driver was unloading diesel fuel into a UST underground storage tank at Maywood NE. The driver did not check tank numbers and unloaded into the wrong tank. The tank he unloaded into did not hold all his load and about 100 gallons overflowed out a vent pipe. The spilled fuel puddled in an area about 20 ft. x 20 ft. Spill pads were used to soak up standing fuel and placed in drums to be disposed of. CHS contacted Haz-Mat Response Inc. (Fed ID # 48-1105367 ) to begin cleanup process. Haz-Mat Response excavated the impacted area and transported all contaminated material to the Lexington Area Solid Waste Agency in Lexington NE.
column169: CHS Transportation is improving our training methods for teaching new drivers how to identify unloading sites. We are teaching them what to do if they are not sure where a load goes and what to do to minimize a spill should one occur. We are in the process of marking our customers tanks better so our drivers can identify the correct one.

column43: REGULAR GASOLINE - MID-GRADE GASOLINE - DIESEL FUEL
column168: CARLOS LYLES THE MCPHERSON COMPANIES, INC (TMC) DRIVER AT APPROXIMATELY 01:30 ON 07/31/2014 WAS GETTING ONTO I-10 EAST BOUND OFF OF BATTLESHIP PKWY IN SPANISH FORT, AL. CARLOS STATES THAT HE HAD SOMETHING IN HIS LEFT EYE AND WAS RUBBING HIS EYE UNDERNEATH HIS GLASSES. HE DID NOT CLEAR THE GUARD RAIL AND THE TRAILER HIT THE GUARD RAIL AND ROLLED THE TRAILER OVER ALONG WITH THE TRACTOR. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER IMMEDIATELY CAUGHT ON FIRE. HE WAS LOADED WITH 8005 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL. MOST OF THE FUEL WAS BURNED IN THE FIRE. AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF THE FUEL WAS SPILLED IN TO THE MOBILE BAY WATERWAY. THE TANKER RUPTURED AS A RESULT OF THE TURNOVER, SEE PICTURES ENCLOSED. UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (USES) WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED WITHIN TWO HOURS TO BEING THE REMEDIATION EFFORTS.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.

column168: THE UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS ONE CARTON CONTAINING ID8000, CONSUMER COMMODITY, CLASS 9 THAT WAS TENDERED TO ALASKA AIRLINES AS PART OF A 43 LOT.  THE PACKAGE WAS MARKED WITH A LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK. INSIDE THE CARTON WERE SIX CANVAS KITS, EACH CONTAINING ONE AEROSOL CANISTER CONTAINING 133 ML OF ID8000. THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO ALASKA AIRLINES IN NEWARK, NJ, AND ARRIVED IN ANCHORAGE, AK ON ALASKA FLIGHT 93 ON JULY 8, 2014. THE ALASKA MASTER AIR WAYBILL NUMBER WAS 027-11578615. EXPEDITORS INTERNATIONAL OF WASHINGTON TENDERED THE SHIPMENT TO ALASKA AIRLINES AS THE FREIGHT FORWARDER ON EXPEDITORS' MASTER REFERENCE EWRT037833, HOUSE BILL REFERENCE H280047045. THE CARGO ON HOUSE BULL H280047045 WAS TENDERED TO EXPEDITORS BY TRIANGLE DISTRIBUTION ON BEHALF OF AMERICAN EAGLE OUTFITTERS AS PART OF AN 8 LOT WEIGHING 104 POUNDS TOTAL. BECAUSE OTHER CONSIGNMENTS WERE SHIPPED AT THE SAME TIME, IN TOTAL, 62 CARTONS WERE SHIPPED ON PALLETS.  TRIANGLE TENDERED THE GOODS AS "APPAREL/MERCHANDISE," AND DID NOT DECLARE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. SINCE AN APPAREL SHIPMENT DID NOT REQUIRE IT, JV TRANSPORTATION DISPATCHED A DRIVER WITH NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRAINING TO PICK UP THE GOODS. FOR THIS REASON, AND THE FACT THAT THE CARGO WAS ON PALLETS, THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTE THE LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK. THE CARGO WAS NOT RECEIVED IN EXPEDITORS' WAREHOUSE, BUT WAS TENDERED DIRECTLY TO ALASKA AIRLINES IN NEWARK BY JV TRANSPORTATION ON BEHALF OF EXPEDITORS. BECAUSE CARGO WAS AT NO TIME IN THE DIRECT POSSESSION OF EXPEDITORS, IT WAS NOT POSSIBLE FOR EXPEDITORS TO SEE THE LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK ON THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE ANCHORAGE CARGO HANDLING FACILITY BY ALASKA AIRLINES PERSONNEL.  THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE OR UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
column169: AMERICAN EAGLE HAS DISCUSSED THIS UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT INTERNALLY, AND WILL CONDUCT A DANGEROUS GOODS MEETING WITH ITS DEPARTMENT HEADS OF SUPPLY CHAIN TO DISCUSS FUTURE SHIPPING NEEDS, AND DEVELOP A PLAN FOR CLASS 9 MATERIAL AS IT PERTAINS TO DIRECT TO STORE SHIPPING FROM TRANSLOADING FACILITIES SUCH AS TRINAGLE DISTRIBUTION.    AMERICAN EAGLE HAS ALSO COMMUNICATED TO TRAINGLE THAT THEY MUST OBTAIN PROPER DANGEROUS GOODS CERTIFICATION TO SHIP DANGEROUS GOODS.    JV TRANSPORTATION, THE TRUCKING COMPANY THAT MOVED THE SHIPMENT FROM TRAINGLE TO THE NEWARK AIRPORT HAS REVIEWD THIS ISSUE WITH ITS OPERATION MANAGERS.  IT WILL INCLUDE DISCUSSIONS OF THE LIMITED QUANTITIES MARK IN ITS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND DOCK HANDLING TRAINING.

column168: THE ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON THE ROADWAY LOCATED ON THE PROPERTY AT 1200 JAY BIRD RD IN PEEBLES, OHIO WHEN AVIATION FUEL BEGAN TO BE RELEASED FROM A LOOSE DOME LID ON THE TRAILER. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF AVIATION FUEL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY. BBU ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: ON JULY 1ST OUR DRIVER PICKED UP A BULK LOAD OF MONETHANOLAMINE AT DOW CHEMICAL IN TEXAS CITY, TEXAS. THE DRIVER LEFT THE FACILITY AND WAS IN TRANSIT TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY. WHILE HE WAS IN TRANSIT (SEABROOK, TEXAS) HE WAS FLAGGED DOWN AND MADE AWARE THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT DRIPPING OUT OF THE TOP OF HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF THE WASH OUT PORT. HE TIGHTENED THE WASH OUT CAP ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. AS HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DOING THAT THE POLICE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP AND TOLD HIM HE COULDN'T MOVE THE TRAILER UNTIL AFTER THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHED OFF THE CONTAMINATED AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DID THEIR DECONTAMINATION AND THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM THE SCENE AND WENT ONTO HIS DELIVERY. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 5 GALLONS OR LESS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER. PLEASE NOTE THAT THE PRODUCT ONLY LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER WHEN IT WAS SLOSHING AROUND AND NOT THE ENTIRE TIME THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING.
column169: IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY HE RETURNED BACK TO THE OFFICE AND WAS INTERVIEWED BY THE SAFETY MANAGER. THEY DISCUSSED THIS INCIDENT IN DETAIL AND LANGER TRANSPORT HAS COME TO THE CONCLUSION THAT THE CLEAN OUT CAP CAME LOOSE  DURING TRANSIT BECAUSE THE CAP WASN'T PROPERLY SECURED. THIS IS SPILL OCCURRED DUE TO OPERATOR ERROR. WE CAME UP WITH THIS THEORY BECAUSE WHEN THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED AND PRESSURE TESTED WE DIDN'T FIND ANY DEFECTS WITH IT. THIS INCIDENT WAS DOCUMENTED IN THE DRIVERS FILE AND HE WENT THROUGH A MANDATORY REFRESHER TRAINING COURSE ON TRAILER INSPECTIONS. ADDITIONALLY WE SENT OUT A MEMO TO OUR DRIVERS ALERTING THEM ABOUT THIS INCIDENT AND HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO CHECK AND VERIFY THAT THE CLEAN OUR CAPS ON THE TRAILER ARE IN PLACE AND PROPERLY SECURE. WE WILL DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.
