column168: THE OPERATOR OF THE TANKER FAILED TO UNLOAD APPROXIMATELY 30 BBLS OF CRUDE OIL AT HIS PREVIOUS OFFLOAD STATION. THE DRIVER DID NOT VERIFY BEFORE LOADING THAT THE OIL WAS INSIDE THE TRAILER AND BEGAN TO FILL HIS TRAILER AND IT REACHED MAX CAPACITY AND OVERFILLED. THE AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE WAS 10 BARRELS.
column169: ALL CENTRAL CRUDE DRIVERS ARE TO ACTIVATE THEIR OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEMS BEFORE LOADING AND UTILIZE THEM WHILE UNLOADING AS WELL. THIS IS A FAIL SAFE DEVICE THAT WILL ALLOW US TO KEEP THE ENVIRONMENT FROM BEING CONTAMINATED.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: FRANK WAS DELIVERING HIS SECOND LOAD OF 64-22 TO THE BRIDGE PORT ASPHALT PLANT FROM WYNNEWOOD, OK. FRANK WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 380 IN DECATOR, TX.  HE TOOK THE 287 NORTHBOUND EXIT. THIS EXT HAS A VERY SHARP RIGHT HAND TURN AND HAS A POSTED SPEED OF 20 MPH. THE EXIT WAS TAKEN TOO FAST AND THE LOAD SHIFTED TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANKER. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER LAID OVER ON THE DRIVER’S SIDE SPILLING ITS LOAD OF PG 64-22 ASPHALT (LIQUID ASPHALT WITH ELEVATED TEMPERATURE).    WHAT WAS DONE TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THE RELEASE:  A BERM OF ASPHALT MILLINGS (RECLAIMED ASPHALT) WAS PLACED AROUND THE SPILL WHILE IT COOLED TO AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WHERE ITS SOLIDIFIED. THE HARDENED, COOLED MATERIAL WAS THEN REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND TRANSPORTED TO A WASTE FACILITY.
column169: THIS SPILL OCCURRED DUE TO OUR DRIVER SPEEDING IN A CURVE.  THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED AFTER A THOROUGH INVESTIGATION AS FAILURE TO SLOW DOWN AND OBEY THE SPEED LIMIT WAS THE DIRECT CAUSE OF THE SPILL. THIS AREA WAS CLEARLY POSTED AND THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW SAFE DRIVING PROCEDURES IN AN AREA THAT HAD GREAT VISIBILITY AND WARNINGS TO ADVISE DRIVERS OF A SLOW CURVE THAT REQUIRED REDUCED SPEED.  WE HAD HIRED A DRIVER WITH EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCE DRIVING THIS TYPE OF TANKER VEHICLE.    THIS VEHICLE AT THE TIME OF THE CRASH WAS RECENTLY PUT IN SERVICE AND WAS THE ONLY ONE BEING USED IN THE AREA IN ORDER TO PICKUP AND DELIVER LIQUID ASPHALT (ELEVATED TEMPERATURE TO OUR ASPHALT PLANT LOCATIONS). DUE TO THIS VEHICLE CRASH WE DECIDED NOT TO CONTINUE THIS UTILIZING THIS TYPE OF VEHICLE IN OUR FLEET IN THE TEXAS AREA AT THIS TIME.  INSTEAD WE WILL CONTACT WITH AN OUTSIDE HAULER TO TRANSPORT LIQUID ASPHALT TO OUR ASPHALT PLANT LOCATIONS IN TEXAS AT THIS TIME.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: MTS TRANSPORT COMPANY LOADED UP A 6,000 GALLON TANKER TRUCK WITH BITUMINOUS CONCRETE (ALSO CALLED LIQUID ASPHALT) AT THE PENNINGTON PARTNERS LOCATED AT 5501 PENNINGTON AVE., BALTIMORE, MD 21226. THERE WERE NO PROBLEMS GETTING THE TRUCK LOADED WITH ASPHALT. THERE WERE NO PROBLEMS TRANSPORTING THE TRUCK OVER THE HIGHWAY TO THE DESTINATION. THE MTS TRANSPORT TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE DESTINATION CALLED KIRBY ASPHALT AT 5411 KIRBY RD, CLINTON, MD 20735. AT 12PM ON JULY 3, 2014 AS THE TRUCK WAS UNLOADING THE LIQUID ASPHALT INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STRAGE TANK (AST) AT THE KIRBY ASPHALT SITE IT OVERLOADED THEAST. SITE PERSONNEL NOTICED THE LIQUID ASPHALT FLOWING INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT DIKE THAT SURROUNDED THE AST. THE TANKER DRIVER STOPPED UNLOADING THE FUEL FROM THE TRUCK. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 200 GALLONS OF LIQUID ASPHALT WAS OVERLOADED AND NOW SITS IN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT DIKE. SITE PERSONNEL REALIZED THAT THEY MISCALCULATED HOW EMPTY THE AST WAS. TURNS OUT THE AST HAD MORE LIQUID ASHPHALT IN IT THAN SITE PERSONNEL HAD CALCULATED THEREFORE IT FILLED UP BEFORE THE LOAD WAS COMEPLETELY DELIVERED FROM THE TANKER DRIVER.    SITE PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE COMPANY ENVIRONMENTAL ADVISOR. SITE PERSONNEL ALSO CALLED THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT (MDE) TO REPORT THE SPILL.  MDE CONFIRMED THE REPORT WITH CONFRIMATION NUMBER 1087958.    NONE OF THE SPILL LEFT THE DIKE. NONE OF THE SPILL LEFT THE SITE. NONE OF THE SPILL ENTERED WATERS OF THE STATE.    THE SPILL WILL REMAIN IN THE DIKE UNTIL IT HARDENS. AFTER IT HARDENS IT WILL BE SCRAPED OUT AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.
column169: THE AREA MANAGER IS GOING TO RETRAIN ALL OF THE SITE PERSONNEL ON HOW TO CALCULATE THE AVAILABLE VOLUME IN THE TANKS TO PREVENT AN OVERFILLING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THE TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHEN IT WAS MOVED TO THE DOCK. THE VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE FOUND DAMAGED AND THE CLAMPS ARE NOT WORKING PROPERLY. A LINED SALVAGE DRUM, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, WAS USED FOR THE CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS. THE DRUM IS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: TOTES AND OTHER VARIOUS KINDS OF PACKAGINGS, CONTAINING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN! ALL TOTES MUST BE BLOCKED, BRACED, SECURED AND SHROUDED FOR ADEQUATE PROTECTION TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGING. USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING. PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!

column168: THE TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 59 NEAR CLEVELAND, TEXAS WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED FIRE COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND NOTIFIED EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. DUE TO THE INTENSE HEAT, THE SEALS ON THE DISCHARGE VALVES WERE COMPROMISED AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF STYTRENE MONOMER WHEN THE PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK TRAILER. MASTERS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ALREADY ON SCENE TO ASSIST WITH THE PRODUCT TRANSFER AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC WILL COMPLETE AN INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE FIRE AND MAKE ANY NECESSARY REPAIRS IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCCURENCE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 A.M. CENTRAL DAYLIGHT TIME (CDT) A TRACTOR-TRAILER, OWNED BY SOUTHWESTERN MOTOR TRANSPORT, INC. (SMTL) WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF GAVIN ROAD AND MILO ROAD IN LAREDO, TX. AS THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A TURN AT THE INTERSECTION, THE LOAD SHIFTED AND THE TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE AND A PORTION OF THE LOAD WAS SPILLED. THE CARGO CONSISTED OF 11 TOTES OF SILOXANE POLYALKYLENEOXIDE COPOLYMER. ONE TOTE WAS DAMAGED AND SPILL ABOUT 150 GALLONS. MOST OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER. IT WAS BELIEVED THAT ONLY ABOUT 20 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE.    WE CONTACTED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (USES) AND REQUESTED A RESPONSE. MR. JUAN GOMEZ, WITH USES, ARRIVED ON THE SITE WITHIN THE HOUR. USES PERSONNEL PLACED A GRANULAR ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE IMPACTED ROAD AND INSIDE TO THE TRAILER TO SOLIDIFY THE PRODUCT. THEY PLACED THE MIXTURE INTO 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THE TRAILER THE FOLLOWING DAY. THEY PRESSURE WASHED THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND COLLECTED THE RINSE WATER FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN WITH REGARD TO THE RESPONSIBLE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THIS ACCIDENT. REMEDIAL HM-126 AND HM 232 TRAINING WAS GIVEN TO THOSE INVOLVED, WITH EMPHASIS ON BLOCKING, BRACING AND GENERAL LOAD SECUREMENT PROCEDURES REQUIRED ON ALL HAZ-MAT FREIGHT/LOADS.

column169: MAKE SURE HOSE TIGHTFILL IS SECURELY ATTACHED.

column168: Driver was driving north bound on 395 when he saw a deer enter onto the road way. He applied the brakes causing the drums to brake free from the rope holding the drums in place. A vehicle behind the tractor/trailer noticed there was something leaking from the trailer and he pulled up to Gene to advise him of the leak. Gene pulled over and verified the leak, at which point he called emergency responders and his supervisor to the scene.The drum was secured with a 1/4" poly rope with 1,100 Ibs per sq inch tinsel strength (per manufacturers specs),wrapped five (5) times around the drums, blocked and braced with other freight. When the brakes were applied to avoid hitting the deer, the rope snapped allowing the drum to slide off the pallet cracking the bottom of the drum.The duration of the release and clean up was approximately 12 hours long.
column169: Recommendation and action taken, load hazardous materials freight in the nose of the trailer, purchase and use athicker 1/2" nylon rope with a greater tensile strength due to the force from a sudden stop.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON RT. 62 IN HUBBARDSTON, MA AND AS HE APPROACHED INTERSECTION OF RT. 68, IT APPEARS HE DIDN'T STOP AT THE STOP SIGN AND ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTH ON RT. 68 COLLIDED WITH THE LEFT REAR DUAL WHEELS OF OUR VEHICLE. THIS IMPACT CAUSED OUR VEHICLE TO GET OF CONTROL AND THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT IT A FEW TIMES UNTIL THE BOBTAIL ROLLED ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE IN THE ROADWAY AND SLID INTO A POLE AT THE EDGE OF THE ROADWWAY. WHEN THE BOBTAIL LAID OVER IN THE ROAD, THE METER BOX PUSHED AGAINST A FLEX HOSE CAUSING A BREAK IN THE VAPOR PIPING. THE VAPOR LEAK WAS EVENTUALLY SHUT OF BY THE RESPONDING FO UPON ADVICE FROM OUR COMPANY PERSONNEL. THE VAPOR LOCATED FOR A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME AND WAS CONTROLLED BY THE FD USING WATER FOG.
column169: WITHIN OUR COMPANY, WE HAVE PUT TOGETHER SAETY BULLETIN INFORMATION REGARDING THIS ACCIDENT FOR ALL OF OUR EMPLOYEES TO BE MORE AWARE TO HELP PREVENT THE SAME THING FROM HAPPENING TO THEM.
